<h1 class="hero-h">Fractional CMO for <em style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif;font-style:italic;color:#00C853;">fintech.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">B2B fintech (payments, infrastructure, banking-as-a-service, lending tech) and B2C fintech (consumer banking, wealth, insurance, lending). Different playbooks, different compliance constraints than typical B2B SaaS. The fractional CMO model fits well in fintech — with a leader who understands the trust requirements and regulatory considerations that shape every campaign.</p>
</div></div>


<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Why fintech is different</span>
<h2 class="h2">Structural differences from generic B2B SaaS</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Trust is the conversion variable, not features.</strong> In financial products, the buyer needs to trust that you won't lose their money, leak their data, or get them in regulatory trouble. Feature comparisons matter less than credibility signals.</li>
<li><strong>Compliance review on customer-facing content.</strong> Less heavy than healthcare but real — claims about returns, security, insurance, lending terms, partner relationships all need scrutiny.</li>
<li><strong>Long sales cycles in B2B fintech.</strong> Banks and large enterprises take 12-18+ months to onboard a new vendor; marketing's job is brand + content + relationship-building over that horizon, not short-cycle lead-gen.</li>
<li><strong>Short, high-velocity cycles in B2C fintech.</strong> Consumer lending, wealth, insurance — high-volume paid + organic acquisition with sophisticated attribution. Different skillset from B2B fintech.</li>
<li><strong>Partner and integration ecosystems matter.</strong> Most fintechs sit in a partner ecosystem (banks, networks, processors, ISVs). Marketing has to address direct customers AND ecosystem partners.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">B2B fintech playbook</span>
<h2 class="h2">What drives growth in B2B fintech</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Sales-led, marketing-amplified.</strong> Enterprise sales motion with marketing-generated air cover. Account-based marketing, executive content, customer case studies as the centerpiece.</li>
<li><strong>Industry-vertical depth.</strong> Generic "we serve all financial institutions" loses to specific "we're built for community banks under $5B in assets." Vertical positioning is high-leverage.</li>
<li><strong>Conference + association presence.</strong> Money 20/20, Fintech Meetup, ABA, ACAMS, etc. Where deals start.</li>
<li><strong>Trust signals everywhere.</strong> SOC 2, PCI-DSS, KYC/AML certifications, banking partnerships, customer logos, board members. The website is a trust-signaling document, not a feature spec.</li>
<li><strong>Compliance content as marketing.</strong> Compliance teams at banks are the actual buyer for many fintech products. Content that helps them with their compliance work creates pull.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">B2C fintech playbook</span>
<h2 class="h2">What drives growth in consumer fintech</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Performance marketing at scale.</strong> Paid acquisition, LTV/CAC discipline, attribution sophistication. Closer to consumer DTC than to B2B SaaS.</li>
<li><strong>Referral + word-of-mouth loops.</strong> Banking and wealth products spread through trust networks; structured referral programs are typically high-ROI.</li>
<li><strong>Onboarding as marketing.</strong> First 30 days in a consumer fintech product predict 12-month retention and referral. The onboarding experience is a marketing surface, not just a product surface.</li>
<li><strong>Trust + security messaging.</strong> Consumer fintech buyers research extensively. Security pages, regulatory disclosures, FAQ content all influence the conversion decision.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">When fractional fits</span>
<h2 class="h2">Stage and shape that match the model</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Fintech context</th><th>Fit</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>Pre-PMF / pre-seed</td><td>Usually no — founder owns marketing</td></tr>
<tr><td>Series A B2B fintech, $1M-$10M ARR</td><td><strong>Strong fit</strong></td></tr>
<tr><td>Series A-B B2C fintech</td><td><strong>Strong fit</strong> with consumer-acquisition expertise</td></tr>
<tr><td>Growth-stage B2B fintech ($10M-$50M ARR)</td><td><strong>Strong fit</strong>, often dual-role with marketing director</td></tr>
<tr><td>Late-stage / pre-IPO fintech</td><td>Usually needs full-time CMO; fractional can bridge during search</td></tr>
<tr><td>Bank or large enterprise financial institution</td><td>Wrong fit — full-time CMO + large team required</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The AI angle</span>
<h2 class="h2">Where AI helps in fintech marketing</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Compliance-aware content drafting.</strong> AI-drafted content with regulatory review built into the workflow — faster cycles, fewer compliance escalations.</li>
<li><strong>Account research and ABM enrichment.</strong> Automated research on target banks, financial institutions, and decision-makers for B2B fintech ABM.</li>
<li><strong>Onboarding nurture sequences.</strong> AI-driven onboarding flows for B2C fintech that adapt to user engagement signals and surface trust-building content at the right moments.</li>
<li><strong>Partner ecosystem outreach.</strong> Programmatic outreach to banking/network/ISV partners with context and personalization.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>


